					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kakroom" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2198340); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2198340&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182915" alt="Kakroom" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2198340)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kakroom" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2198340); return false;" >Kakroom</a></span> <span class="odate time_1503885260 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">28 Aug 2017 01:54</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3579859">
									

<p>I was unsure whether the spag errors in the interview and UIU report were intentional and indicative that 633 was still affecting the system from within or if they're just oversights until the comments section, so - that's a thing. Perhaps that aspect of the piece was too subtle for me to grasp.</p>
<p>Other than that, it's pretty well constructed, as previously indicated - the graphic's high quality, the FBI's perspective feels appropriately 'X-Filey' in that this definitely qualifies as one of those unassuming-but-deadly skips that could easily fit into the sweet spot where they come in, and it leaves off on a nice bit of fridge logic. I don't really have strong thoughts on it one way or another; it was an enjoyable article with not too much chaff.</p>

							</div>

								
					
